Just about five-eighths (of a century) ago there was a sharp discontinuity: algebra began to appear on the pages of the statistician's, journals. The pioneering work of Karl Pearson spread out in many directions; that of Student spread out in many others, including the analysis of economic time series. Since that time the tools of the statistician have been sharpened on the grindstone of algebra and hammered out on the anvil of mathematical models. We learned rapidly that, to a far greater extent than we had dared to think, one could use data to deal both with the uncertainties of nature and with the uncertainties of data-based results. ~ John Tukey 
